SIMPLE: frigid
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Frigid
<hw>Frig"id</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>frigidus</ets>, fr. <ets>frigere</ets> to be cold; prob. akin to
Gr. <?/ to shudder, or perh. to <?/ cold. Cf. <er>Frill</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Cold; wanting heat or warmth; of low temperature;
<as>as, a frigid climate</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Wanting warmth, fervor, ardor, fire, vivacity, etc.;
unfeeling; forbidding in manner; dull and unanimated; stiff and formal;
<as>as, a <ex>frigid</ex> constitution; a <ex>frigid</ex> style; a
<ex>frigid</ex> look or manner; <ex>frigid</ex> obedience or
service.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Wanting natural heat or vigor sufficient to excite
the generative power; impotent.</def> <rj><au>Johnson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Frigid zone</b></col>, <cd>that part of the earth which
lies between either polar circle and its pole. It extends 23<?/ 28<?/
from the pole. See the Note under <er>Arctic</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Frigidarium</ent>⟦br⟧
